### Part 1 — Investigation
#### (1) Current Understanding
All three thinkers would agree that the "system" is not a static artifact but a living dialectical process. Fichte would emphasize the system as the historical embodiment of the I's ethical self-positing; Schelling, as the unfolding of nature's self-revelation in time; Hegel, as the Absolute Spirit's self-realization through world-history. Yet each would reject the others' characterization: Fichte sees Schelling's nature-philosophy as prematurely objectifying the I; Schelling views Hegel's logic as a "cold tomb" freezing living spirit;
